s a richly human document as well as an illuminating treatise on race, gender, and class dynamics. While presenting larger social trends Yung highlights the many individual experiences of Chinese American women, and her skill as an oral history interviewer gives this work an immediacy that is poignant and effective. Her analysis of intraethnic class rifts—a major gap in ethnic history—sheds important light on the difficulties that Chinese American women faced in their own communities. Yung provides a more accurate view of their lives than has existed before, revealing the many ways that these women—rather than being passive victims of oppression—were active agents in the making of their own history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChinese American womenxHistoryxCaliforniaxSan Francisco. 0aChinese American womenzCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistory. 0aWomen immigrantsxHistoryxCaliforniaxSan Francisco. 0aWomen immigrantszCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistory. 4aUSA. 4agender studies. 4agender. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory. 4asociology of sex. 4asociology. 4awomen. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  aautobiographies.  acustom of footbinding.  aenglish and chinese newspapers.  aengrossing.  aexperiences of chinese american women.  afirst half of 20th century.  agovernment census records.  alargest chinese population in us.  aoral history interviews.  asan francisco.  asocial change in lives of women.  astages of unbinding.  astudy of chinese american women.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008867240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520915350?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978052091